d the family. Entangled Emancipation reveals how the complex relationship between the divided Germanys in the early Cold War catalysed but sometimes blocked efforts to reshape legal understandings of gender and the family after decades of inequality. Using methods drawn from gender history and discourse analysis, the book restores the history of the women’s movements in East and West Germany. Entangled Emancipation ultimately explores the parallel processes through which East and West Germany reimagined, negotiated, and created new civil laws governing women’s rights after the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDomestic relationszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aEqualityzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's rightszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aEast and West Germany.  aEuropean history.  acomparative history.  aentanglement history.  aequal rights.  afamily history.  agender equity.  agender history.  apostwar Germany.  awomen's rights.  awomen's studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148755029540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487550295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487550295/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles